{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652283"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18531"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18531"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11263"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1865"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"10696"},{"type":"tags","id":"10717"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26118"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProper chromosome segregation during meiosis is essential for producing gametes with the correct chromosome number. Errors in chromosome separation can result in conditions like trisomy 21 (Down syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of nondisjunction during meiosis I?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sister chromatids fail to separate","Crossing over occurs between non-homologous chromosomes","Centromeres split prematurely","Chromosomes fail to replicate","Homologous chromosomes move to the same pole"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn meiosis I, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehomologous chromosomes move to the same pole\u003C/strong\u003E during nondisjunction instead of separating to opposite poles as they should. This results in an uneven distribution where one daughter cell receives both members of a chromosome pair while the other receives none.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESister chromatids fail to separate\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes nondisjunction in meiosis II, not meiosis I\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrossing over occurs between non-homologous chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - While this can cause problems, it is not nondisjunction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentromeres split prematurely\u003C/strong\u003E - This would cause premature sister chromatid separation, not nondisjunction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChromosomes fail to replicate\u003C/strong\u003E - Chromosome replication occurs before meiosis begins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe resulting gametes will have either two copies or zero copies of the affected chromosome. In the case of a normal gamete fertilising a gamete with two copies, the resulting embryo will now therefore have three copies of that chromosome (trisomy).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nondisjunction in meiosis I occurs when homologous chromosome pairs fail to separate, resulting in gametes with extra or missing chromosomes.","Meiosis I nondisjunction differs from meiosis II nondisjunction in that entire homologous chromosomes, rather than sister chromatids, fail to separate.","Chromosomal nondisjunction during gamete formation is the primary cause of trisomy conditions like Down syndrome."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Ghosh S, Feingold E, Dey SK. Etiology of Down syndrome: Evidence for consistent association among altered meiotic recombination, nondisjunction, and maternal age across populations. Am J Med Genet A. 2009 Jul;149A(7):1415-20. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2732749/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18531"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T20:07:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T20:08:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11263"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79790"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attribu